name: solid-state-optical-measurements-laboratory
notes: The Solid State Optical Measurements Laboratory is a research laboratory available to thesis and dissertation students for optical diagnostics on solids, particularly semiconductors and semiconductor structures such as superlattices. Experimental facilities are available for measurement of laser excited luminescence, excitation spectroscopy, time resolved spectroscopy, cathodoluminescent spectroscopy, and absorption spectroscopy. The laboratory contains four working state-of-the-art luminescent systems, one for each of the above measurements. Each system is housed in a separate room and each includes an excitation source, a low temperature liquid He cryostat, a monochromator, suitable detection equipment and a dedicated computer for data acquisition and statistical analysis and modeling. Laboratory equipment includes an 18 Watt Nd:YVO4 laser pumping a Ti:Sapphire oscillator and regenerative amplifier capable of generating 8 microjoule pulses at a 100kHz repetition rate at 50 femtoseconds. This system can also pump an Optical Parametric Amplifier, which can extend the wavelength range from the ultraviolet (0.266 microns) to the infrared (1.6 microns), several Janis Liquid Helium Cryostats (T= 1.2K to 300K), Helium refrigerators, and Helitran systems (T= 8 K to 3 00K), krypton and argon ion lasers, a tunable laser source consisting of a Ti:Sapphire laser providing excitation wavelengths of 275nm to beyond 1 micron, a pulsed nitrogen laser and a pulsed dye laser, a cathodoluminescent electron beam system providing beams of energy 100eV to 20keV at beam currents of microamps to milliamps, two &#190; M and two &#189; M monochromaters, a &#190; M Triple Spectrometer, as well as optical detectors covering the range of wavelengths from the ultraviolet to the mid infrared. Facilities for absorption spectroscopy include a BioRad Fourier Transform Infrared Spectrometer and a Perkin-Elmer Visible/Ultraviolet Spectrometer.
